              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a scheme (or an algebraic space) of finite type over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, and assume it to be separated.
    Then there exists a diagram

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2380</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.1.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         X         \xleftarrow {\alpha } Y_\bullet          \hookrightarrow  \overline {Y}_\bullet        \tag{8.2.1.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    in which <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is the complement of a normal crossing divisor in a smooth and proper simplicial scheme <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Y}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, and is a proper hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    We have ((II) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.xml" number="5.3.5" />)

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2381</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.1.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)         \xrightarrow {\sim } \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y_\bullet ).       \tag{8.2.1.2}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree></fr:p>
                <fr:p>In <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19.xml" number="8.1.19" />, we endow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> with a mixed Hodge structure.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex> be the mixed Hodge structure on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)]]></fr:tex> induced by <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.1.2" />.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2887</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.2</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>With the above notation, the mixed Hodge structure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {\mathscr {H}}(\alpha )]]></fr:tex> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)]]></fr:tex> is independent of the choice of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\alpha ]]></fr:tex>.
    We call it the <fr:em>mixed Hodge structure of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex></fr:em>.
    For every morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X_1\to  X_2]]></fr:tex> of schemes, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X_2)\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X_1)]]></fr:tex> is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1662</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#241</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-241.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The proof uses <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8" href="hodge-theory-iii-6.2.8.xml" number="6.2.8" />, and is parallel to that of (C) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.11" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.11.xml" number="3.2.11" /> (cf. also [hodge-theory-iii-8.3.3 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>]).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2888</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.3</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>For smooth <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we can show, by taking <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {Y}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> to be a constant simplicial scheme, that the mixed Hodge structure in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.2" /> coincides with that defined in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.12" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.12.xml" taxon="Definition" number="3.2.12" />.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2889</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.4</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The pairs <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)]]></fr:tex> such that the Hodge number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[h^{pq}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X)]]></fr:tex> are non-zero satisfy the following conditions:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(p,q)\in [0,n]\times [0,n]]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\dim  X=N]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geqslant  N]]></fr:tex>, then
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           (p,q)\in [n-N,N]\times [n-N,N].         ]]></fr:tex>
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iii) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is proper, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+q\leqslant  n]]></fr:tex>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(iv) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is smooth, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+q\geqslant  n]]></fr:tex>.
        The same conclusion holds if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is an equidimensional "rational homology manifold" of dimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[N]]></fr:tex>, i.e. if, for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex>,
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \operatorname {H}^i_{(x)}(X,\mathbb {Q})           =           \begin {cases}             0 &\text {if }i\neq  2N           \\\mathbb {Q} &\text {if }i=2N.           \end {cases}         ]]></fr:tex>
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p><fr:p><fr:embedded-tex hash="5d5d4b1665baee6d5a31251d0d4f7b2e"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzpicture}[point/.style={circle, fill=black, inner sep=0pt, minimum size=2.5pt}]
      \begin {scope}
        \draw [->] (0,0) to (3,0) node[label={below:$p$}]{};
        \draw [->] (0,0) to (0,3) node[label={left:$q$}]{};
        \node [below] at (2,0) {\scriptsize $N$};
        \node [left] at (0,2) {\scriptsize $N$};
        \node [below] at (1.3,0) {\scriptsize $n$};
        \node [left] at (0,1.3) {\scriptsize $n$};
        \draw [dashed] (2,0) to (2,2.7);
        \draw [dashed] (0,2) to (2.7,2);
        \draw  (0,1.3) to (1.3,1.3) to (1.3,0) to cycle;
        \node  at (0.5,0.2) {\scriptsize  proper};
        \node  at (0.8,1.1) {\scriptsize  smooth};
      \end {scope}
      \begin {scope}[shift={(4,0)}]
        \draw [->] (0,0) to (4,0) node[label={below:$p$}]{};
        \draw [->] (0,0) to (0,3) node[label={left:$q$}]{};
        \node [below] at (2.35,0) {\scriptsize $N\qquad  n$};
        \node [left] at (0,2) {\scriptsize $N$};
        \node [left] at (0,2.7) {\scriptsize $n$};
        \draw [dashed] (2,0) to (2,2.7);
        \draw [dashed] (0,2) to (2.7,2);
        \draw [dashed] (2.7,0) to (0,2.7);
        \draw  (0.7,2) to (2,2) to (2,0.7) to (0.7,0.7) to cycle;
        \draw  (0.7,2) to (2,0.7);
        \node  at (1.2,0.9) {\scriptsize  proper};
        \node  at (1.5,1.8) {\scriptsize  smooth};
      \end {scope}
    \end {tikzpicture}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex></fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1703</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#242</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-242.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Claim (ii) will be proven in [hodge-theory-iii-8.3.10 <fr:strong>(?)</fr:strong>].
      Claim (i) follows from (iii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.1.20" />.
      For proper <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, we can find a diagram as in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.1.1" /> in which <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet =\overline {Y}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>, and (iii) then follows from (iv) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.1.20" />.
      For smooth <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, (iv) follows from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.3.xml" number="8.2.3" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.15" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.15.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="3.2.15" />.
      The general case then follows: if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p\colon \widetilde {X}\to  X]]></fr:tex> is a resolution of singularities of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is injective, since the Poincaré dual transpose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p_!]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet _\mathrm {c}(X,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet _\mathrm {c}(\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is a retraction for it.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2890</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.5</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is proper.
    If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[u\colon  Y\to  X]]></fr:tex> is a surjective proper morphism, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> smooth, then the weight-<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> quotient of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> is the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.
    The sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2846</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.5.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})         \to  \operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})         \xrightarrow {\operatorname {pr}_1^*-\operatorname {pr}_2^*} \operatorname {H}^n(Y\times _X Y,\mathbb {Q})       \tag{8.2.5.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is exact.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2847</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#243</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-243.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be as in <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.1.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.1.1" />, with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_0=Y]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y_\bullet =\overline {Y}_\bullet ]]></fr:tex>.
      By (ii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.20.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.1.20" />, we have an exact sequence

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2848</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.5.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           0           \to  \operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})/W^{n-1}\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^n(Y_0,\mathbb {Q})           \underset {\delta _1}{\overset {\delta _0}{\rightrightarrows }} \operatorname {H}^n(Y_1,\mathbb {Q})         \tag{8.2.5.2}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      which implies <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.5" /> (conversely, this exact sequence can easily be deduced from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.5" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.7" /> below).</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2891</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.6</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.6.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.6</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       Y       \xrightarrow {f} X       \overset {j}{\hookrightarrow } \overline {X}     ]]></fr:tex>
    be morphisms of schemes.
    Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is proper and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is smooth, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}]]></fr:tex> is a smooth compactification of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> have the same image in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1713</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#244</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-244.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.6</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>The proof is parallel to that of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.18" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.18.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="3.2.18" />.
      It suffices to prove, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i]]></fr:tex> and any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W(f^*)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W((jf)^*)]]></fr:tex> have the same image in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.

      
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>n]]></fr:tex>, these images are both zero since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})=0]]></fr:tex> ((iii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.2.4" />).
        </html:li>

        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<n]]></fr:tex>, these images are both zero since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})=0]]></fr:tex> ((iv) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.2.4" />).
        </html:li>

        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i=n]]></fr:tex>, these images are equal since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(j^*)]]></fr:tex> is surjective (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.17" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.2.17.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="3.2.17" />).
        </html:li>

      </html:ol></fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2892</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.7</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \widetilde {X}       \xrightarrow {\pi } X       \xrightarrow {f} Y     ]]></fr:tex>
    be morphisms of schemes.
    Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is smooth, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is proper, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {X}]]></fr:tex> is smooth and proper, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi ]]></fr:tex> is surjective.
    Then the kernels of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^*]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(f\pi )^*]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> are equal.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2893</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#245</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-245.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>We will prove that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Ker}(\operatorname {Gr}_i^W(f^*))=\operatorname {Ker}(\operatorname {Gr}_i^W((f\pi )^*))]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.

      
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i<n]]></fr:tex>, these kernels are both zero since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})=0]]></fr:tex> ((iv) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.2.4" />).
        </html:li>

        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i>n]]></fr:tex>, these kernels are both all of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(Y,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_i^W\operatorname {H}^n(X,\mathbb {Q})=0]]></fr:tex> ((iii) of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.4.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.2.4" />).
        </html:li>

        
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
          For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[i=n]]></fr:tex>, these kernels are equal since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_n^W(\pi ^*)]]></fr:tex> is injective (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.5.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.5.2" />).
        </html:li>

      </html:ol></fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2898</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.8</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \widetilde {X}       \xrightarrow {\pi } X       \overset {f}{\hookrightarrow } Y     ]]></fr:tex>
    be morphisms of schemes.
    Suppose that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex> is smooth and proper, that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a closed subscheme of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y]]></fr:tex>, and that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\widetilde {X}]]></fr:tex> is a resolution of singularities of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q=f\pi ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U=Y\setminus  X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then the sequence

    <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2899</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.8.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})         \xrightarrow {q_!} \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})         \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (U,\mathbb {Q})       \tag{8.2.8.1}       ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

    is exact.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2900</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#246</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-246.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>By <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.7.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.7" />, we have that
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \operatorname {Ker}(f^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q}))         = \operatorname {Ker}(q^*\colon \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})\to \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})).       ]]></fr:tex>
      The long exact sequence in cohomology of the pair <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Y,X]]></fr:tex> thus gives an exact sequence

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2901</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.2.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.2.8.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \operatorname {H}_c^\bullet (U,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})           \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (\widetilde {X},\mathbb {Q})         \tag{8.2.8.2}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

      and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.1.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.8.1" /> is the transpose sequence of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.2.xml" taxon="Equation" number="8.2.8.2" /> under Poincaré duality.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2902</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.9</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.9.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.9</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p><fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.8.xml" taxon="Corollary" number="8.2.8" /> is used under more general hypotheses in [<fr:link type="local" href="G1968.xml" addr="G1968" title="Le groupe de Brauer, III: Exemples et compléments">G1968</fr:link>, (9.7), p. 161].
    As Lieberman remarked, the justification given loc. cit. is insufficient.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:p>From <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.25" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.25.xml" number="8.1.25" /> we deduce the following:</fr:p>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2903</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.10</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.10.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.10</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <fr:p>The Künneth isomorphisms
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X\times  Y,\mathbb {Q})       \simeq  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X,\mathbb {Q})\otimes \operatorname {H}^\bullet (Y,\mathbb {Q})     ]]></fr:tex>
    are isomorphisms of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:anchor>2904</fr:anchor>
                <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.2.11</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.11.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:number>8.2.11</fr:number>
                <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2</fr:parent>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>The cup product
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)\otimes \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)       \to  \operatorname {H}^\bullet (X)     ]]></fr:tex>
    is a morphism of mixed Hodge structures.</fr:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2905</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="machine">#247</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-247.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.2.11</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>This follows from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.10" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.10.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.10" /> and from <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.2.2.xml" taxon="Proposition" number="8.2.2" /> applied to the diagonal morphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Delta \colon  X\to  X\times  X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
              <fr:backmatter />
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
    <fr:tree toc="false" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
      <fr:frontmatter>
        <fr:title text="Related">Related</fr:title>
        <fr:authors />
      </fr:frontmatter>
      <fr:mainmatter>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2952</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>5.3.5</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>The fundamental results, proven in [<fr:link type="local" href="SD.xml" addr="SD" title="Techniques de descente cohomologique">SD</fr:link>], are the following.

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(I) &quot;">
        The continuous maps of universal cohomological descent form a Grothendieck topology on the category of topological spaces, which we call the <fr:em>universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(II) &quot;">
        A proper (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-0.1" href="hodge-theory-iii-0.1.xml" number="III.0.1" />) surjective map is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(III) &quot;">
        A map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> that admits sections locally on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of universal cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(IV) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\colon  X_\bullet \to  S]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated augmented simplicial space (with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  k\leqslant \infty ]]></fr:tex>).
        For <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k\geqslant  n\geqslant -1]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varphi _n\colon \operatorname {cosq} X_\bullet \to \operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> be the evident map.
        We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>-truncated hypercover of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, for the universal cohomological descent topology</fr:em>, if the maps

        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2141</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>5.3.5.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-5.3.5</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[             (\varphi _n)_{n+1}             \colon  X_{n+1}             \to  (\operatorname {cosq}\operatorname {sq}_n X_\bullet )_{n+1}           \tag{5.3.5.1}           ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>

        (for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-1\leqslant  n\leqslant  k-1]]></fr:tex>) are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\bullet ]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover, then the simplicial space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {cosq}(X_\bullet )]]></fr:tex> augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is of cohomological descent.
      </html:li>


      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(V) &quot;">
        Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of simplicial topological spaces augmented over <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           \begin {CD}             X_\bullet  @>a>> Y_\bullet            \\@VxVV @VVyV           \\S @= S           \end {CD}         ]]></fr:tex>
        We say that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:em>hypercover</fr:em> for the universal cohomological descent topology if the evident maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X_n\to (\operatorname {cosq}_{n-1}^{Y_\bullet }\operatorname {sq}_{n-1}X_\bullet )_n]]></fr:tex> are of universal cohomological descent.
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is such a hypercover then, for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[K\in \operatorname {Ob}\mathrm {D}^+(S)]]></fr:tex>,
        <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           a^*\colon            \mathrm {R} y_*y^*K           \xrightarrow {\sim } \mathrm {R} x_*x^*K.         ]]></fr:tex>
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" expanded="false" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:anchor>2953</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:authors />
            <fr:number>8.1.19</fr:number>
            <fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.1</fr:parent>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We now apply <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.13" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.13.xml" number="8.1.13" /> and <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.15" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.15.xml" taxon="Theorem" number="8.1.15" /> to <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.12" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.12.xml" taxon="Example" number="8.1.12" />.</fr:p><fr:p>We obtain a mixed Hodge complex consisting of (a), (b), and (c) below.</fr:p>
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
      The complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\Gamma \mathrm {R} j_*\mathbb {Z}\simeq \mathrm {R}\Gamma (U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>, whose cohomology groups are the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
      The filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta (W,L)]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\Gamma \mathrm {R} j_*\mathbb {Q}\simeq \mathrm {R}\Gamma (U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Q})]]></fr:tex>.
      With the notation of <fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.4" href="hodge-theory-ii-3.1.4.xml" number="3.1.4" />, we have
      <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[         \begin {aligned}           \operatorname {Gr}_n^{\delta (W,L)}\mathrm {R}\Gamma (U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Q})           &\underset {(7.1.6.5)}{\simeq } \bigoplus _m \operatorname {Gr}_{n+m}^W \mathrm {R}\Gamma (U_m,\mathbb {Q})[-m]         \\&\simeq  \bigoplus _m \mathrm {R}\Gamma (\widetilde {Y}_m^{n+m},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{n+m}[-n-m])[-m]         \\&= \bigoplus _m \mathrm {R}\Gamma (\widetilde {Y}_m^{n+m},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{n+m})[-n-2m].         \end {aligned}       ]]></fr:tex>
      
      The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1]]></fr:tex> page of the corresponding spectral sequence is the sum of the groups of form <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^p(\widetilde {Y}_q^r,\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^r)]]></fr:tex>;
      this contributes to the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^{p+q+r}(U_\bullet )]]></fr:tex>;
      it corresponds to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Gr}_a^{\delta (W,F)}]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p+2r=(p+q+r)+a]]></fr:tex>:

      <fr:tree toc="true" numbered="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" expanded="true" root="false" xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1434</fr:anchor><fr:addr type="user">hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19.1.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Equation</fr:taxon><fr:authors /><fr:number>8.1.19.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-8.1.19</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[           {}_{\delta (W,L)}E_1^{-a,b}           = \bigoplus _{\substack {p+2r=b\\q-r=-a}} \operatorname {H}^p(\widetilde {Y}_q^r,\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^r)           \Rightarrow  \operatorname {H}^{-a+b}(U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Q}).         \tag{8.1.19.1}         ]]></fr:tex></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
    </html:li>


    
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(c) &quot;">
      The bifiltration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(\delta (W,L),F)]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}\Gamma \mathrm {R} j_*\mathbb {C}\simeq \mathrm {s}\mathrm {R}\Gamma ^\bullet \Omega _X^\bullet (\log  D)]]></fr:tex>.
    </html:li>

  </html:ol>
<fr:p>The filtration <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> endows <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_{\delta (W,L)}E_1^{-a,b}]]></fr:tex> with a Hodge structure of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex>, and the differentials <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[d_1]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_{\delta (W,L)}E]]></fr:tex> are the morphisms of the Hodge <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>-structures.
    The complex <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{}_{\delta (W,L)}E_q^{\bullet  b}]]></fr:tex> is the simple complex associated the double complex of Hodge structures of weight <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> given by:
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[       \small        \begin {CD}         \operatorname {H}^{b-2(r+2)}(\widetilde {Y}_{q+1}^{r+1},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{r+1})[-r-1] @>{\mathrm {Gysin}}>> \operatorname {H}^{b-2r}(\widetilde {Y}_{q+1}^{r},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{r})[-r] @>{\mathrm {Gysin}}>> \operatorname {H}^{b-2(r-2)}(\widetilde {Y}_{q+1}^{r-1},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{r-1})[-r+1]       \\ @. @A{\sum _i(-1)^i\delta _i}AA @AA{\sum _i(-1)^i\delta _i}A       \\ @. \operatorname {H}^{b-2r}(\widetilde {Y}_q^r,\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^r)[-r] @>>{\mathrm {Gysin}}> \operatorname {H}^{b-2(r-2)}(\widetilde {Y}_q^{r-1},\varepsilon _\mathbb {Q}^{r-1})[-r+1]       \end {CD}     ]]></fr:tex>
    The indices in the terms in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[E_1^{ab}]]></fr:tex> satisfy <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[-a=q-r]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>In particular, the <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {H}^n(U_\bullet ,\mathbb {Z})]]></fr:tex> are endowed with mixed Hodge structures (<fr:ref addr="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.9" href="hodge-theory-iii-8.1.9.xml" taxon="Scholium" number="8.1.9" />).</fr:p></fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
